Analysis of Data Science Job Postings on Glassdoor¶

The goal of this project is to identify trends, patterns and key factors that influence job postings and to analyze which idustries, sectors or companies hire data scientists, data anlyst, Business Intelligenece developer (data jobs) .Understand the pay range across diffrent sector and industry.¶

Project Goals :¶

  • Clean and transform the raw/uncleaned data for analysis and visualization
  • Perform Exploratory data analysis (EDA) to identify trends, patterns in the data

Data Cleaning and Transformation¶

In [16]:
# Define a function to update job titles based on specific patterns
def update_job_titles(job_title):
    if pd.notna(job_title):
        job_title = job_title.lower()
        if 'data science' in job_title or 'data scientist' in job_title or 'software engineer' in job_title:
            return 'Data Scientist' + (' - Senior' if 'senior' in job_title else '')
        elif 'data analyst' in job_title or 'data analysis' in job_title or 'data insights analyst' in job_title:
            return 'Data Analyst'+ (' - Senior' if 'senior' in job_title else '')
        elif 'business intelligence'in job_title:
            return 'Business Intelligence Analyst'+ (' - Senior' if 'senior' in job_title else '')
        elif 'ml' in job_title or 'ai' in job_title or 'machine learning' in job_title:
            return 'Machine Learning Engineer'+ (' - Senior' if 'senior' in job_title else '')
        elif 'data engineer' in job_title or 'data analytics engineer' in job_title or 'data integration and modeling engineer' in job_title or 'principal data & analytics platform engineer' in job_title or 'production engineer - statistics/data analysis' in job_title:
            return 'Data Engineer'+ (' - Senior' if 'senior' in job_title else '')
        elif 'analytics manager' in job_title:
            return 'Analytics Manager'
        elif 'data modeler' in job_title:
            return 'Data Modeler'
        elif 'data architect' in job_title:
            return 'Data Architect'
        else:
            updated_title = job_title         
                  
        return updated_title 
    
# Apply the update_job_titles function to the 'Job_Title' column
df['new_job_title'] = df['job_title'].apply(update_job_titles)

In [19]:
# salary estimate is of object data type, now we will convert into int type and will split salry into lower and upper bound salary
# as we can see salary estimate column has '$' and 'K' symbols, so lets remove that too.
df.loc[:, 'salary_estimate'] = df['salary_estimate'].apply(lambda x: x.split('(')[0])
df.loc[:, 'salary_estimate'] = df['salary_estimate'].apply(lambda x: x.replace('K', '').replace('$', ''))

Name: salary_estimate, dtype: object
In [21]:
# Extracting minimum salary from 'Salary Estimate' 
df['minimum_salary'] = df['salary_estimate'].apply(lambda x: int(x.split('-')[0]))

# Extracting maximum salary from 'Salary Estimate' 
df['maximum_salary'] = df['salary_estimate'].apply(lambda x: int(x.split('-')[-1]))

# Calculation for avrage salary
df['average_salary'] = (df['minimum_salary'] + df['maximum_salary']) / 2

# To do analysis on data jobs, lets first find out skills from job description
skills = ['R','Python','Excel','SQL','Tableau', 'Power BI','Hadoop', 'Spark']

# Creating columns for each skill and fill them with 0 initially
for skills in skills:
    df[skills] = 0

# For each skills, updating corresponding column if skills is found 
    df[skills] = df['job_description'].str.contains(skills, case=False, na=False).astype(int)

# Finding out the distribution of jobs per sector
sector_counts = df['sector'].value_counts()

# Creating bar plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sector_counts.plot(kind='bar')

# Add labels and title
plt.xlabel('Sector')
plt.ylabel('Number of Jobs')
plt.title('Number of Jobs Per Sector')

# Show the plot
plt.show()

# Job Skills 
skills = ['R','Python','Excel','SQL','Tableau', 'Power BI','Hadoop', 'Spark']

jobs_skill = df[skills].sum()

# Creating bar plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
jobs_skill.sort_values().plot(kind='bar')

# Adding labels and title
plt.xlabel('Skills')
plt.ylabel('Number of Jobs')
plt.title('Number of Jobs per Skill')

# Show the plot
plt.show()

# scatter plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

plt.ylabel('Company Rating')
plt.title('Correlation between Company Ratings and Average Salary')

# Show the plot
plt.show()

The Information Technology sector has the highest number of jobs posting, so I highly recommend that data scientists, data analyst apply more jobs in this sector.

Howeve, The avrage salary is low in Informaytion technology sector as compared to Consumer and bar plot shows that the Media, Aerospace companies has the highest paying jobs.

In skills perspective, R language has the most importance than the Python as it is requested by the most of the companies.
